<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>
<Weakness xmlns="http://cwe.mitre.org/cwe-7" xmlns:xhtml="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" ID="431" Name="Missing Handler" Abstraction="Base" Structure="Simple" Status="Draft">
         <Description>A handler is not available or implemented.</Description>
         <Extended_Description>When an exception is thrown and not caught, the process has given up an opportunity to decide if a given failure or event is worth a change in execution.</Extended_Description>
         <Related_Weaknesses>
            <Related_Weakness Nature="ChildOf" CWE_ID="691" View_ID="1000" Ordinal="Primary" />
            <Related_Weakness Nature="CanPrecede" CWE_ID="433" View_ID="1000" />
         </Related_Weaknesses>
         <Weakness_Ordinalities>
            <Weakness_Ordinality>
               <Ordinality>Primary</Ordinality>
            </Weakness_Ordinality>
         </Weakness_Ordinalities>
         <Applicable_Platforms>
            <Language Class="Not Language-Specific" Prevalence="Undetermined" />
         </Applicable_Platforms>
         <Modes_Of_Introduction>
            <Introduction>
               <Phase>Implementation</Phase>
            </Introduction>
         </Modes_Of_Introduction>
         <Common_Consequences>
            <Consequence>
               <Scope>Other</Scope>
               <Impact>Varies by Context</Impact>
            </Consequence>
         </Common_Consequences>
         <Potential_Mitigations>
            <Mitigation>
               <Phase>Implementation</Phase>
               <Description>Handle all possible situations (e.g. error condition).</Description>
            </Mitigation>
            <Mitigation>
               <Phase>Implementation</Phase>
               <Description>If an operation can throw an Exception, implement a handler for that specific exception.</Description>
            </Mitigation>
         </Potential_Mitigations>
         <Demonstrative_Examples>
            <Demonstrative_Example>
               <Intro_Text>If a Servlet does not catch all exceptions, it may reveal debugging information that will help an adversary form a plan of attack. In the following method a DNS lookup failure will cause the Servlet to throw an exception.</Intro_Text>
               <Example_Code Nature="Bad" Language="Java">
                  <xhtml:div>protected void doPost (HttpServletRequest req, HttpServletResponse res) throws IOException {<xhtml:div style="margin-left:1em;">String ip = req.getRemoteAddr();<xhtml:br />InetAddress addr = InetAddress.getByName(ip);<xhtml:br />...<xhtml:br />out.println("hello " + addr.getHostName());</xhtml:div>}</xhtml:div>
               </Example_Code>
               <Body_Text>When a Servlet throws an exception, the default error response the Servlet container sends back to the user typically includes debugging information. This information is of great value to an attacker.</Body_Text>
            </Demonstrative_Example>
         </Demonstrative_Examples>
		 <Observed_Examples>
		   <Observed_Example>
			 <Reference>CVE-2022-25302</Reference>
			 <Description>SDK for OPC Unified Architecture (OPC UA) is missing a handler for when a cast fails, allowing for a crash</Description>
			 <Link>https://www.cve.org/CVERecord?id=CVE-2022-25302</Link>
		   </Observed_Example>
		 </Observed_Examples>
